><br />If __NFDBITS is signed (and it is), and "d" is a signed type, that<br />division and modulus now create stupid extra code with conditionals<br />(assuming 'd' isn't constant, of course).<br /><br />So changing the sign of __NFDBITS has these kinds of subtle side<br />effects that clearly the glibc people didn't actually think about.<br /><br />What was the *advantage* of that stupidity?<br /><br />Quite frankly, if you want to make NFDBITS be an "int", then it should<br />have been done at that<br /><br />   #define NFDBITS ((int)__NFDBITS)<br /><br />level, not at "__NFDBITS". Exactly because the unsigned type there matters.<br /><br />Does anybody in the glibc camp care about efficient and small code AT ALL?<br /><br />                  Linus<br /><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
